post_text:
Free Meals for All AUHSD Students!

On Monday, August 31, 2020, the U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA) released Summer Meal Program Waiver Extensions that allows schools to run the Summer Seamless Option instead of the National School Lunch Program and Breakfast Program, allowing us to serve any child (0-18 years) at no charge. These waivers are in response to the nationwide COVID-19 pandemic. Per CDE, this will be effective immediately (August 31, 2020) through December 2020.

Free Meals for All AUHSD Students!

On Monday, August 31, 2020, the U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA) released Summer Meal Program Waiver Extensions that allows schools to run the Summer Seamless Option instead of the National School Lunch Program and Breakfast Program, allowing us to serve any child (0-18 years) at no charge. These waivers are in response to the nationwide COVID-19 pandemic. Per CDE, this will be effective immediately (August 31, 2020) through December 2020.

Attention AUHSD Students: Young Congressional Leaders Opportunity

The YCL program will provide a unique opportunity for you to learn about the branches of government, legislation, civic engagement, and to make connections with peers from schools across Orange County. All students currently attending high school within the 46th District are welcome to apply and may do so by visiting: https://buff.ly/34KnyC3.

Along with meeting your local officials and gaining networking opportunities, YCL graduates may receive letters of recommendation for college, job, and scholarship applications. Internship opportunities in my District office are also available to YCL graduates.The YCL program will begin with an Orientation Session on Saturday, Sept. 12, 10 a.m. to 12 p.m., on Zoom. Additional session dates and topics are listed on the attached flyer.

The "Beast" is the nickname of the world‚Äôs first off the grid, fully sustainable, completely green 100% solar powered freezer unit turned on at Anaheim High School.

After three years of planning and building, "The Beast" was created from a forty foot refrigerated cargo container, designed to ship food. During a power outage, its solar technology will generate its own green power, virtually eliminating food waste, and operate completely off of the electrical grid.

post_text: We had our first #AUHSD District English Learner Advisory Committee (#DELAC) meeting of the year with over 100 people in attendance! It was excellent to virtually see our parents and teams come together. Great to hear from Superintendent Michael Matsuda speak about the vision for the year; DIrector of Special Programs Joe Carmona spoke about the Learning Continuity and Attendance Plan; FACES Coordinator Araceli Chavez speak about our virtual parent academies; and Araceli Huerta spoke about the free COVID-19 testing we are offering through our partnership with Latino Health Access. #UnlimitedYou #AUHSDELMS

post_text: As we welcome new teachers all over #AUHSD, I wanted to take moment to welcome our newest Vietnamese World Language teacher, Tulinh Doung, to our team. She is our third Vietnamese teacher in AUHSD and the first at Loara HS! As you can see, from the photos [taken a year ago], Tulinh has been actively engaged in Vietnamese teaching and learning through #TAVIET. If you are at Loara HS and interested in taking Vietnamese, now is your chance! AUHSD takes interdistrict transfers if you are outside the District and want to join.

A Message from AUHSD Health Services

AUHSD Families,

We want to remind families that immunizations are still required for your students to begin virtual learning. Families Together of Orange County will be offering their mobile unit medical services this Friday August 14th From 9am-5pm and Monday August 17th From 9am-5pm at the District Office. You can call 949-349-1062 to schedule an appointment for immunizations. Your student will have 10 days to clear their immunization record from the first day of school. If you have any questions please contact your school's Health Technician via email. Please see the attached flyer for more information.

post_text:
Great article by AUHSD's Kasey Spencer!

Ms. Spencer is an English teacher at Oxford Academy, with over two decades of experience in her field. Her work ethic and dedication to challenging students to discover their voice through writing resulted in her being named the 2016 Anaheim Union High School District Teacher of the Year. In addition to teaching, she also serves as an EdTech Coach and most recently has been instrumental in the academic development and online education training of teachers at Cambridge Virtual Academy, an all-online institution serving students from 7th-12th grade.

shared_text:
Deb Pham
July 15 at 5:15 PM ¬∑

Thanks to Amazon for providing me an opportunity to attend the CSTA 2020 conference on July 13-14th (CSTA -Computer Science Teachers Association). There were more than 2,900 attendees from all over the US. 140 sessions were available for me to attend during those two short days. I learned and got so much resources from the professionals and experts. I am enriched with many different teaching techniques and practices that relate to computer science, distance teaching, anti-racism, and equity. I am so excited to use them in the next school year.

We Want to Hear Your Voice AUHSD Families!

Your input is critical to the opening of AUHSD schools for the 2020-2021 school year. We are asking that ALL AUHSD families take the short survey that was emailed to you by Friday, July 10. Your replies will ensure we have accurate data when planning for classrooms and instruction of your student.

The survey was sent by AUHSD via Aeries Communications. Please make sure your email address is accurate and your settings allow emails/text. You may also want to check your Junk/Spam mail folder, if needed.

Thank you!

post_text:
AUHSD staff and their family members volunteered to distribute over 500 face shields this week to our students and parents working in essential jobs. We have also donated over 600 face shields and several hundred ear savers to healthcare organizations and non-profits.

The face shields were produced by Walker Junior High School teachers Jack Gupton and Nich Takehara using 3D printers and laser cutters from our STEAM classes, and AIME partners the Anaheim YMCA and the Anaheim White House hosted the distribution sites.

Thanks also to Walker JHS teacher Ron Latham for his work delivering shields, and Cypress HS teacher Kevin Dwyer for producing the ear savers, as well as our district staff members, PTSAs, and AIME partners Catarina's Club and Anaheim Public Utilities, who have provided funding for materials to produce the shields. We are still accepting donations for materials and equipment to produce more shields, please visit https://forms.gle/7Ld7XdeqZs156dJf8 if you would like to donate.

post_text:
Congratulations to AUHSD alum, Cadet Iwonka Gabriela Niscior, daughter of Ryszard and Patricia Niscior who will graduate from the U.S. Military Academy on Saturday, June 13!

Iwonka graduated from J.F. Kennedy High School in 2016. While at West Point, she concentrated her studies in French. She was commissioned as a second lieutenant in the U.S. Army within the Air Defense branch and will report to Fort Campbell, KY., for her first assignment.

The mission of the U.S. Military Academy is to educate, train, and inspire the Corps of Cadets so that each graduate is a commissioned leader of character committed to the values of Duty, Honor, Country and prepared for a career of professional excellence and service to the Nation as an officer in the United States Army.

Thank you to Principal Amber Houston for sharing.

post_text: Super proud to announce #AUHSD seniors earned 1,077 Seal of Biliteracy awards in fifteen different languages in 2020! We had 37 students earn Triliteracy Awards. We also added five new languages this year with students earning the award in Pashto, Khmer, Gujarati, Russian and Romanian! Our eighth grade students did a great job as well increasing the number of AUHSD and #OCDE Pathway to Biliteracy awards to over 400! Huge thanks to our students, staff and families for making this happen, as well as a shout-out to Claudia Mercado and our ELMS LAC team for their diligent and innovative work assessing remotely! #AUHSD #UnlimitedYou #AUHSDUnlimitedYou #CalTog

Anaheim High School's Performance Arts Conservatory Wins Big in the Spirit of the Macy's Awards!

Congratulations to AHS Students, Sharon King, Oscar Gonzalez, and Anaheim High School's Performance Arts Conservatory whose production of "In the Heights" was nominated as the "Show of the Year" and "Best Choreography" by the Spirit of the Macy's! AHS students and APAC were nominated in top 5 in OC for Best Show, Choreography, and Best Actor! AHS student Andrew Gutierrez won the top award and a $1,000 scholarship!! Beautiful job and way to bring home the CIF Championship of High School Performing Arts!!!

post_text:
Countdown to Graduation!

We want to thank all of our families for their continued support and cooperation throughout these unprecedented times and look forward to celebrating with you the accomplishments of the graduating Class of 2020 during our Drive Thru Graduations and Virtual Graduations for each of our sites. Please see the attached schedules for more details regarding these two events.

Please be aware that in light of recent COVID-19 cases within our community, we have been advised to take extra precautions during upcoming events for the safety of our students, staff, and community. This includes having students and their families remain inside their vehicles during textbook collection, technology collection, and diploma distribution during our drive thru graduations. Site staff members will approach each vehicle to collect or distribute all appropriate items. The safety and security of our students and staff is our top priority and we have taken these measures to ensure that our families and community remain healthy and safe.

post_text:
The Final Shamrock News: Kennedy High School

For the past eight years, The Shamrock newspaper staff released a bi-weekly morning news broadcast for the students at John F. Kennedy High School. These short films were written, produced, and edited by journalism students to be broadcast to the school during 2nd period classes. While the production of The Shamrock News could often be tedious and stressful, it was a labor of love for Kennedy students and advisors. Today marks the FINAL edition of The Shamrock News!

The following video honors the student journalists who served on staff and helped to create so many wonderful memories. Enjoy! https://youtu.be/VMDkdwmF73E

Special thank you to all the Kennedy students that participated and Shamrock News advisor, Mr. Matthew Corcoran.

Congratulations to Western High School for being recognized as a 2020 California Democracy School (AUHSD's 5th School to be Recognized This Year)!

AUHSD has the most schools (15) of any district in California to be recognized as Democracy Schools. Western joins the following other AUHSD schools: Ball JHS, Brookhurst JHS, Cypress HS, Dale JHS, Katella HS, Kennedy HS, Lexington JHS, Loara HS, Magnolia HS, Orangeview JHS, Oxford Academy, Savanna HS, South JHS, and Walker JHS.

Each of the California Democracy Schools listed have dedicated time, resources, policies, and expertise to institutionalize high quality civic learning to prepare ALL students for civic life in the 21st century.

An Important Message From AUHSD Food Services: Get Help Buying Food While Schools are Closed

Because schools are closed due to COVID-19, children who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals can get up to $365 in food benefits in addition to their grab and go meals from one of our 8 school sites. These food benefits are called Pandemic EBT or P-EBT. To learn more please see the attached flyer and the following website:
https://www.cdss.ca.gov/home/pandemic-ebt

post_text:
Congratulations to Ball Junior High School for being recognized as a 2020 California Democracy School!

AUHSD has the most schools (14) of any district in California to be recognized as Democracy Schools. Ball joins the following other AUHSD schools: Brookhurst JHS, Cypress HS, Dale JHS, Katella HS, Kennedy HS, Lexington JHS, Loara HS, Magnolia HS, Orangeview JHS, Oxford Academy, Savanna HS, South JHS, and Walker JHS.

Each of the California Democracy Schools listed have dedicated time, resources, policies, and expertise to institutionalize high quality civic learning to prepare ALL students for civic life in the 21st century.

The Federal Aviation Administration is inviting students who are Minecraft enthusiasts to join its 2020 Aviation and Space Education (AVSED) Airport Design Challenge that will run now through June 1.

Participants will research a local airport of their choosing and then recreate that airport from the ground up in the virtual world of Minecraft! Students, who can work individually or in small teams, will receive weekly instruction from FAA airport development experts. Award certificates will be provided for grades K-6 and 7-12. For more details, visit https://buff.ly/3dqFXos

Congratulations to Walker Junior High School's Phoemela Juan and other AUHSD students being recognized by Soapbox Nation fro their great speeches.

Students stood up and spoke out on an issue that matters to them - and now their speeches can be seen by the world at www.facebook.com/SoapboxNation!

Soapbox Nation will be awarding a $20 gift card to the first 125 speech submissions, and selecting 12 winners to give their speech at a live, virtual Mainstage event in June.

If you have more students with great speeches that should be amplified by Soapbox Nation - it's not too late for them to submit! The deadline is May 10, and here are the submission instructions you can share with them: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1vvmoS0bK4fRcrzGb5NdI-qbPjJy4LXl7mqfyysJZ2Ls/edit?usp=sharing

Our communities need to listen to young people now more than ever!

post_text:
Another great day at Anaheim HS of cap & gown and "bling" for senior recognition!

Out of the 466 cap & gowns we started with on Monday 4/27, AHS only has 26 left!

Additionally, AHS handed out a bunch of CTE cords, Dual Language stoles, NHS cord, medals & stoles, Principal's Honor roll medallions, Puente stoles.

We know there is more "bling" arriving this week and on Monday 5/4.

They gave a lot of "WOOT WOOT" shout outs to the seniors who came by...big thanks to the teachers and staff who came by.

It was a blast of hooting, hollering, congratulating and dancing around their cars!

In addition to amazing instructional aides, clerical Marcella Deem and Terry Dancer, we also had Joe Casas, Bobby Flowers, Sergio Hernandez, Cindy Miceli, Oscar Ramirez, Christina Spandikow & Doug Wager with admin today. It was quite the "physical distancing" and celebratory party for our deserving seniors.

Please see attached photos...students were so sweet and smiled a lot!

Thank you to Assistant Principal Alison Konrad and the rest of the AHS team for sharing.

COVID-19 Capstone Student Work:

Loara High School math students have been working on a COVID-19 writing and data analysis project.

They have focused on the following:

1. The Impact of the Coronavirus
2. Food Intake & Obesity in the U.S. (and how COVID-19 has changed the way we eat due to shortages in grocery stores and restaurant closures, etc)
3. A Day in the Life of a Teen (students get to create data about themselves pre-Coronavirus, and now, how they spend their time each day while under lockdown)

Below are the sites:

Math 3 student work: https://padlet.com/turner_k/Math3Per1_4_6

Math 5 student work: https://padlet.com/turner_k/Math5Per3

AP Calculus BC student work: https://padlet.com/turner_k/CalcBCPer2

Special thanks to Mrs. Kelly Turner and her students for sharing their great work. Check out Mrs. Turner's Graph of the Week website for more information and lessons: https://www.turnersgraphoftheweek.com/info--contact.html

South Junior High School Student Council students have been busy trying to find ways to make a positive impact on our student body. On top of taking care of their academic obligations, they have put together a series of Public Service Announcements. Each PSA delivers a timely message. The topics range from information about COVID19, tutorials on how to make hand sanitizer, ideas for how to cure boredom, and even ways to manage stress during these challenging times. The PSA's will be published on the South Facebook page each week.

post_text:
My Isolation: The Blog of a Lifetime

Coyote Mesa, a senior at MHS, completed the following website for his COVID Capstone project: https://singingcoyotemesa.wixsite.com/mysite-1

In the site, Coyote writes:
"I started this blog from inspiration from my friend, Lohith. He has a blog called The Diary of Corona. My blog is a little different, more set on the foundation of what I'm doing during this quarantine and my daily life, rather than to the up-to-date facts of this devastating pandemic."

"I'm a student at Magnolia High School. I'm an overall nerd, who is interested in many different facets of life. At school, I've been involved in esports, cybersecurity, public speaking, and theatre, to name a few. In the near future, I plan on studying Computer Science at CSU Long Beach."

Coyote's posts include:
"Surviving in a Negative Environment"
"My Life in Quarantine"
"Life is Like League of Legends"and more

Special thank you to Coyote and Magnolia HS teacher, Mr. Robin Turner for sharing.

post_text:
AUHSD Stories: Walker JHS: Civic Learning in Action

[Video was shot before school dismissals]

Earlier this year, the city of La Palma installed two new traffic signs on the corner of La Luna and Walker street directly across the street from Walker JHS and adjacent to Kennedy. This is a major thoroughfare for students walking to and from school and, unfortunately, the location of many close calls between cars and pedestrians.

After some extensive research, Walker students began a campaign and ultimately met with city leaders to present their case. After several meetings and deliberation with the city council, the city agreed with students and installed "No right turn on a red when children are present" signs.

This is a great example of tenacity and civic engagement by students to make their community safer. Special thanks to teachers Valerie Armijo and Tina Alvahuante and Principal Jennifer Brown for sharing: https://youtu.be/rr24EH_TILQ

Via LA Times Journalist and AUHSD Friend, Anh Do:

Are you the parent of a student who will be missing prom this year? We need your help getting the word out to your students and their friends: The L.A. Times is throwing a virtual prom for students missing what should be one of the most memorable nights of their life. It still can be memorable!

Participation is easy ‚Äì and doesn‚Äôt involve leaving the house: A student who wants to attend our virtual prom should send us a photo of themselves, and a separate photo of their date or friend group, all wearing their prom formal wear. (If they never got as far as shopping, they can just find something fancy in the closet.) Then, we will work a little Photoshop magic and voila! They‚Äôll be at our virtual prom. You can see all the submission details here:

https://www.latimes.com/lifestyle/story/2020-04-14/online-prom-photoshop

The deadline to participate is fast approaching: We need submissions by end of day, Pacific time, on Wednesday, April 22.

AUHSD has been named one of the nation‚Äôs Best Communities for Music Education by the NAMM Foundation. Fewer than 5% of school districts nationwide receive this distinction and it recognizes the district‚Äôs commitment to music education.

Now in its 21st year, the Best Communities for Music Education designation is awarded to districts that demonstrate outstanding achievement in efforts to provide music access and education to all students. To qualify for the Best Communities designation, District Visual and Performing Arts Director, Brian Belski responded to detailed questions about funding, graduation requirements, music class participation, instruction time, facilities, and support for the music programs. Responses were verified and then and reviewed by The Music Research Institute at the University of Kansas.

Congratulations to our amazing teachers, students, administrators, and parents for earning this tremendous honor! #auhsdvapa #musiceducation #nammfoundation #AUHSDUnlimitedYou

#AUHSDCapstone: COVID-19

Dear AUHSD Family/Community,

In the upcoming weeks we will be posting some of the remarkable work our students and teachers across our District are creating focused on an #AUHSDCapstone project with the following Driving Question: How Is the Coronavirus Affecting Your Life?

Today, we want to share with you what Lexington‚Äôs photo classes, led by teacher Elizabeth Hind, are working on. Students have created a photovoice project by photographing their lives during the COVID-19 confinement and writing statements about their thoughts and experiences. This is an important project, as photographers document history, and these students are generating primary sources that future generations will use to learn about our time.

Below are a few examples, however, the complete gallery is on view at http://www.instagram.com/photographers.interrupted.

#AUHSDCapstone #AUHSD #UnlimitedYou

Please join us in congratulating four amazing students from Oxford Academy for their accomplishment with MathWorks M3 Modeling Challenge and winning scholarship prizes!

Student Team Members: Bill Feng (Gr 12), Juliana Phan (Gr 12 ), Justin Yue (Gr 12 ), and Kaushal Shyamsundar (Gr 12)
Coach: Ms. Susie Min

These four students worked on a mathematical modeling problem for 72 hours utilizing mathematical expertise, research, and brainstorming to evaluate data and build a solution. Oxford Academy's Math Modeling Team was recognized as one of the top 22 teams out of 760 teams that participated across the country. The team will receive $1,000 scholarship as part of their recognition.

M3 Challenge is a competition designed to motivate students to study and pursue careers in applied math, computational science, and technical computing sponsored by Society for Industrial and Applied Mathematics.

post_text:
AUHSD COVID-19 Update: 3/20 (6:00PM)

Dear AUHSD Family/Community,

Yesterday, Governor Newsom issued an open-ended statewide ‚ÄúStay at Home‚Äù order. While AUHSD learns more about what this means for our District in the coming days, education is still considered an essential service. This means that AUHSD will continue to provide the following nutritional and educational essential needs to our community:

Food Services (including during spring break)

Distance Learning

Student Technology

Please continue to check your emails and AUHSD social media for updates and information. As AUHSD has more information, we will keep our community informed.

Thank you for your partnership and understanding as we navigate these unprecedented times together.

As we approach spring break, we hope you and your family stays healthy and strong. Have a wonderful spring break and we look forward to reconvening for distance learning on March 30th.

Enrichment to Distance Learning/At-Home Learning from PBS SoCal

Many Southern California schools are closed due to the coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak, causing thousands of students to be without access to educational instruction.

As part of the public media mission to ensure all kids, regardless of their capabilities, have access to continued free educational resources at home, PBS SoCal | KCET, in partnership with LAUSD and in collaboration with California PBS stations, are offering broadcast programming and accompanying digital resources that adhere to California‚Äôs state curriculum to provide continued at-home learning.

In the link below, you will find resources to expand learning and family engagement with their At-Home Learning on-air programming: https://www.kcet.org/at-home-learning

post_text:
We ‚ù§Ô∏è our AUHSD Maintenance and Operations, Plant Managers, Custodians and Athletic Field Workers!

Yesterday, the District's Maintenance and Operations team thoroughly disinfected school sites in their entirety including inside classrooms, doors and door-knobs, quad areas, bathrooms, and other common areas. Staff arrived at the sites at 6a.m. to ensure work was completed by 10a.m.

In addition, maintenance workers have been on site yesterday and today repairing several roof leaks caused by the last rain. This is in an effort to prevent water leaks from causing mold and to prevent future leaks.

Thank you to AUHSD's Maintenance and Operations team and all AUHSD Plant Managers for their outstanding work throughout this week and for being a great support to the District's students, teachers, and staff.

(Thank you to Principal Lorena Moreno from Dale Junior High school for the picture below)

post_text:
Feeding our Families

In the last three days, our AUHSD Food Services staff has served the following number of meals to our community:

Monday, 3/16: 1220
Tuesday, 3/17: 1764
Wednesday, 3/18: 2564

In addition, we want to give a special shout-out to an amazing group of teachers at Magnolia High School who felt the need to support our students and families during this time of uncertainty. A teacher started a document that allowed staff to add names of students who they are finding out have needs and they delivered food to families today. It was really great to see smiling faces on kids and parents.

Thank you to the following Magnolia High School staff for helping deliver food today: Katrina Mundy, Rick Penn, Martin Leyva, Michelle, Brenda Vasquez, Lindsay Ruben, Kathy Look, Kelly, Helen, and Linda Villagomez.
